Change-Id: Ic281c72235f5ed019f11b2ac1a1aaafce7f87718","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/606e8afd4ab34b0c733462b670bb5956641143c6"},{"sha":"cb7f144b577a92d655d8f8c0243219c1dab7dab3","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Pull legacy contrib behavior out of ResourceSummaryWriter

This refactors ResourceSummaryWriter to remove the `v2` parameter, which previously controlled whether the behavior reflected `create_summary_writer()`, aka the legacy tf.contrib.summary API, or `create_summary_writer_v2()`, the API exposed in TF 2. Instead, we just split the behavior into two distinct implementations, `_LegacyResourceSummaryWriter` for contrib and `_ResourceSummaryWriter` for TF 2. This makes each implementation simpler to read in advance of further changes to this class hierarchy.

The symbols have been given leading underscores to discourage their direct usage (since users should refer to the `SummaryWriter` interface only), and I've updated `NoopSummaryWriter` to `_NoopSummaryWriter` accordingly.

[{"sha":"26a2fdcd97033b62854825ac8ace0f681615649c","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Make CreateSummaryFileWriter generate unique filename on every execution

This moves the anti-filename-collision logic from `tf.summary.create_file_writer()` from the Python code wrapping the `CreateSummaryFileWriter` op down into the op kernel itself (specifically, into the `SummaryFileWriter` class in C++). This ensures that we actually get a new filename each time the op executes. Previously this was only true in eager mode - in graph mode, the uniquified `filename_suffix` that the Python code generates would get baked into the graph and reused across executions. Without the suffix uniquification, filenames generated in the same second on the same machine are identical and will clobber each other.

The suffix still consists of the general form `<pid>.<uid>.<user-provided-suffix>`, with two changes:

1. The `uid` is no longer `ops.uid()` but instead a new dedicated counter.
2. In the new logic, if the user-provided suffix doesn't begin with `.` we add one, which avoids some awkwardness in the construction.

Test coverage is added at both the C++ and Python levels.
